---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout>
  <section aria-labelledby="welcome-heading">
    <p
      class="text-foreground-muted mb-6 font-mono text-xs select-none"
      aria-hidden="true"
    >
      $ cat README.md
    </p>
    <h1 class="text-primary mb-4 text-3xl font-bold" id="welcome-heading">
      Omakasui
    </h1>
    <p class="text-foreground mb-4 text-[1.1rem] leading-[1.8]">
      Inspired by <a
        href="https://dhh.dk"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener"
        title="David Heinemeier Hansson's website">DHH</a
      >'s <a
        href="https://omacom.io"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener"
        title="Omacom — DHH's opinionated software collection">Omacom</a
      > philosophy, <em>Omakasui</em> is a curated collection of opinionated post-installation
      scripts for Linux — made by <a
        href="https://lucapattocchio.dev"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener">Kasui</a
      >. One command, zero hassle: get a ready-to-use system tailored to your
      workflow and preferences.
    </p>
    <p class="text-foreground-secondary text-[1.05rem] leading-[1.8]">
      The name is a play on <em>Omakase</em> ("I'll leave it up to you" in Japanese)
      and doubles as a tribute to DHH's Omacom. The philosophy is the same: opinionated,
      curated, functional.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="philosophy-heading">
    <h2
      class="text-foreground-muted mb-3 font-mono text-xs font-normal"
      id="philosophy-heading"
    >
      $ cat philosophy.md
    </h2>
    <p class="text-foreground-secondary mb-4">
      Every Omakasui script is a single <code class="text-primary font-mono"
        >curl | bash</code
      > away. No manual configuration, no dependency hell, no endless decision fatigue.
      You run it once and you get a coherent, functional environment ready to work
      in.
    </p>
    <p class="text-foreground-secondary">
      The setup is opinionated by design. You trust it — the same way you trust
      a good package manager — and focus on what actually matters.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="projects-overview-heading">
    <h2
      class="text-foreground-muted mb-3 font-mono text-xs font-normal"
      id="projects-overview-heading"
    >
      $ ls projects/
    </h2>
    <ul class="text-foreground-secondary space-y-2">
      <li>
        <span class="text-primary font-mono">omabuntu</span> — opinionated post-install
        script for Ubuntu, inspired by Omakub
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="text-primary font-mono">omadeb</span> — the same experience on
        Debian
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="text-primary font-mono">dotfiles</span> — personal configuration
        files, ready to use
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-4">
      <a href="/projects" title="Browse all projects">Browse all projects →</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="author-heading">
    <h2
      class="text-foreground-muted mb-3 font-mono text-xs font-normal"
      id="author-heading"
    >
      $ whoami
    </h2>
    <p class="text-foreground-secondary">
      Built and maintained by <a
        href="https://lucapattocchio.dev"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener">Luca Pattocchio</a
      > (Kasui), a developer based in Italy. The source is on <a
        href="https://github.com/omakasui"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener">GitHub</a
      > and everything ships under the MIT License.
    </p>
  </section>
</Layout>
